        "content": "<p>Yes, it is obvious that there is no natural number between <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>n</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">n</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.4306em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">n</span></span></span></span> and <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>n</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">n+1</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6667em;vertical-align:-0.0833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">n</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">+</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6444em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">1</span></span></span></span> for <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>n</mi><mo>∈</mo><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">N</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">n \\in \\mathbb{N}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.5782em;vertical-align:-0.0391em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">n</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">∈</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6889em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathbb\">N</span></span></span></span>.</p>\n<p>My question is to ask what the name / terminology is for the mathematical reason. </p>\n<p>Intuitively and informally I might say \"the natural numbers are spaced evenly, 1 apart, so there can be no number between <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>n</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">n</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.4306em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">n</span></span></span></span> ands <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>n</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">n+1</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6667em;vertical-align:-0.0833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">n</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">+</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6444em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">1</span></span></span></span>, but this is unsatisfactory. Evenly spaced apart suggests a richer space within which they are spaced apart eg the real number line.</p>\n<p>Another approach is to say that it is by definition. The Peano axioms are such that the successor of a natural number <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>n</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">n</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.4306em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">n</span></span></span></span> is <strong>defined</strong> as <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>n</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">n+1</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6667em;vertical-align:-0.0833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">n</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">+</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6444em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">1</span></span></span></span>, and thus there can be no other successor. If this is the real reason - does it have a name to summarise the idea better than \"evenly spaced\"?</p>",
        "id": 482772158,
        "sender_full_name": "rzeta0",
        "timestamp": 1731765523
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>of course, first off there exists the question of what you mean by \"inbetween\". if by that you mean the order theoretic property, that's just by definition of the order on Nat.</p>",
        "id": 482772357,
        "sender_full_name": "Edward van de Meent",
        "timestamp": 1731765686
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>a slightly more abstract way of saying that the natural numbers have this property, is by saying that there is a <a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/find/?pattern=SuccOrder#doc\">docs#SuccOrder</a> instance for natural numbers where the successor function is equal to <code>fun n =&gt; n + 1</code></p>",
        "id": 482772530,
        "sender_full_name": "Edward van de Meent",
        "timestamp": 1731765831
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>(note that the co-notion for this is <a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/find/?pattern=PredOrder#doc\">docs#PredOrder</a> )</p>",
        "id": 482772598,
        "sender_full_name": "Edward van de Meent",
        "timestamp": 1731765867
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>by \"in between <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>n</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">n</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.4306em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">n</span></span></span></span> and <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>n</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">n+1</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6667em;vertical-align:-0.0833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">n</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">+</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6444em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">1</span></span></span></span>\" I mean there is no natural number <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>x</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">x</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.4306em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">x</span></span></span></span> such that <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>n</mi><mo>&lt;</mo><mi>x</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mo>∧</mo><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>x</mi><mo>&lt;</mo><mi>n</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>1</mn><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">(n&lt;x) \\land (x&lt;n+1)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">n</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">&lt;</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">x</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">∧</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">x</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">&lt;</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6667em;vertical-align:-0.0833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">n</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">+</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">1</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span>.</p>\n<p>sorry I don't know about \"order theoretic\" but I guess it means some objects have an order relation eg \"&lt;\" and \"&lt;=\" eg natural but not complex numbers?</p>",
        "id": 482774597,
        "sender_full_name": "rzeta0",
        "timestamp": 1731767350
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>\"order theoretic\" just means \"related to order theory\".</p>\n<p>I think probably a <a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/find/?pattern=LocallyFiniteOrder#doc\">docs#LocallyFiniteOrder</a> which is also a <a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/find/?pattern=LinearOrder#doc\">docs#LinearOrder</a> (which implies dosc#SuccOrder) is probably closer to what <span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"724904\">@rzeta0</span>  has in mind. </p>\n<p>A locally finite order is one where bounded intervals are finite sets. This is the case for <code>ℕ</code> (e.g., <code>Set.Icc (a : ℕ) b</code> is finite for every <code>a b : ℕ</code>). A linear order just means that any two elements are comparable in the order (i.e., <code>∀ a b, a ≤ b ∨ b ≤ a</code>).</p>\n<p>In some sense, local finiteness is the opposite (not the <em>negation</em>) of a <a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/find/?pattern=DenselyOrdered#doc\">docs#DenselyOrdered</a> type. A densely ordered type is one where, for any two elements <code>a b</code> with <code>a &lt; b</code>, there is a third element <code>c</code> with <code>a &lt; c ∧ c &lt; b</code>. For example, <code>ℚ</code> is densely ordered, and so is <code>ℝ</code>.</p>",
        "id": 482783538,
        "sender_full_name": "Jireh Loreaux",
        "timestamp": 1731774532
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>thanks for the replies - I should have been clearer in the original question.</p>\n<p>I'd like to know the \"maths\" reason, not the \"Mathlib\" reason.</p>\n<p>so far my understanding is that by definition (Peano axioms) a natural number can only have one successor.</p>",
        "id": 482787607,
        "sender_full_name": "rzeta0",
        "timestamp": 1731777906
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I would say that this is indeed by definition: both Peano axioms and Lean's formalization of the natural numbers assume that there is a function from Nat to Nat.  The value of that function on <code>n</code> is called \"the successor of <code>n</code>\".</p>",
        "id": 482787788,
        "sender_full_name": "Damiano Testa",
        "timestamp": 1731778065
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>On top of that, completely arbitrarily, there is a notion of <code>&lt;</code> on natural numbers that declares every natural number to be strictly less than its successor.</p>",
        "id": 482787862,
        "sender_full_name": "Damiano Testa",
        "timestamp": 1731778111
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I personally view the order relation as something that is not part of what the natural numbers \"are\", but what is introduced to study their properties.</p>",
        "id": 482787916,
        "sender_full_name": "Damiano Testa",
        "timestamp": 1731778175
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I personally view this as subsets of subsets of subsets with stricter and stricter conditions</p>",
        "id": 482788047,
        "sender_full_name": "Bo Qin",
        "timestamp": 1731778292
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>For example, even natural numbers is just natural numbers with one additional condition</p>",
        "id": 482788127,
        "sender_full_name": "Bo Qin",
        "timestamp": 1731778337
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>another example would be prime numbers would be a subset of odd numbers</p>",
        "id": 482788212,
        "sender_full_name": "Bo Qin",
        "timestamp": 1731778435
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>even though when you think of prime numbers, you wouldn't think of the conditions required for odd numbers, but it's strictly a subset nonetheless</p>",
        "id": 482788305,
        "sender_full_name": "Bo Qin",
        "timestamp": 1731778492
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>except 2 lol</p>",
        "id": 482788434,
        "sender_full_name": "Bo Qin",
        "timestamp": 1731778614
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>The oddest prime of them all</p>",
